In C++, there isn't a direct equivalent to Python's `pass` statement, but you can achieve similar functionality using an empty statement, which is simply a semicolon (`;`). This can be used in places where a statement is syntactically required but you don't want to perform any operation.

Here's an example:

```cpp
for (int i = 0; i < 10; ++i)
{
    if (i % 2 == 0)
        ;  // This is an empty statement, doing nothing for even numbers
    else
        std::cout << i << " is odd\n";
}
```

In this example, the semicolon after the `if` condition acts as a placeholder that does nothing when the condition is true. This is similar to how `pass` is used in Python.
